In .NET MAUI 10, Android enables **edge-to-edge** by default, which means the old `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` (and MAUI's `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize`) no longer drives layout changes. You need to react to **window insets** instead.

### Quick fix — handle IME insets on Android

In your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Keep adjustResize so the system dispatches IME insets
        Window!.SetSoftInputMode(SoftInput.AdjustResize);

        // React to keyboard insets and pad the content accordingly
        var content = FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(content, new ImeInsetsListener());
    }

    private class ImeInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use the larger of IME or nav-bar so the input bar clears both
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

### Why this works

| .NET 9 (pre-edge-to-edge) | .NET 10 (edge-to-edge) |
|---|---|
| `AdjustResize` shrank the window | Window is full-screen; insets tell you what's occluded |
| Layout auto-adjusted | You apply padding/margin from `WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()` |

### Tips

- **Keep** `AdjustResize` in the manifest/code — it causes the system to dispatch IME insets; without it you won't get callbacks.
- If you want **smooth keyboard animation**, use `WindowInsetsAnimationCompat.Callback` instead of the static listener — it gives you per-frame progress.
- **iOS** already handles this correctly via `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` in MAUI, so no changes needed there.
